Part A: Triple Timeframe Stack 

88
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:31,520
One timeframe shows you a signal. 
Three timeframes show you the truth. 

89
00:09:31,520 --> 00:09:37,600
Most traders do this completely wrong. You 
see a signal on the 1-hour chart and take  

90
00:09:37,600 --> 00:09:44,320
it immediately. You don't check what the daily 
is doing. You're flying blind. You're gambling. 

91
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:50,400
Here's what I do instead. I stack three 
timeframes in a specific order. Daily  

92
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:59,200
tells me the trend—which side of zero is MACD on? 
That's my bias. 4-hour shows me the setup—is there  

93
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:07,360
a crossover or divergence happening? That's my 
signal. 1-hour gives me the entry—is the histogram  

94
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:15,040
confirming with a flip? That's my trigger.
Real quick—watch this trade setup. Daily MACD  

95
00:10:15,040 --> 00:10:21,280
above zero. That means I'm bullish. 
4-hour showing a bullish crossover  

96
00:10:21,280 --> 00:10:27,280
above. That's my signal forming.
1-hour histogram just flipped  

97
00:10:27,280 --> 00:10:34,560
from red to green. That's my entry 
trigger. That’s a 200 point winner. 

98
00:10:34,560 --> 00:10:42,400
The magic is that all three timeframes must agree. 
If the daily is bullish but the 4-hour is bearish,  

99
00:10:42,400 --> 00:10:49,440
I pass. If the 4-hour has a signal but 
the 1-hour doesn't confirm, I wait. 

100
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:54,800
You don't need to overcomplicate this. 
Pick your three timeframes using a 4x  

101
00:10:54,800 --> 00:11:02,560
multiplier. If you trade the 15-minute, check 
the 1-hour and 4-hour. If you trade the 1-hour,  

102
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:06,560
check the 4-hour and daily. Simple.
